<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,151,644]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,319,223,248]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[337,425,223,247]" captionStart="FIGURES 39 – 44" captionStartId="15.[151,263,1870,1893]" captionTargetBox="[151,1432,195,1813]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1436,195,1823]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 39 – 44. Discepholcia, Tambana, Xanthomanthis, adults and male genitalia. 39 – Discepholcia caerulea, male, Thailand (AP); 40 – Tambana variegata, male, Vietnam (GR); 41 – Xanthomantis cornelia, male, South Korea (NIAST); 42 – Discepholcia caerulea, male genitalia, China, genit. prep. HHL- 1767 - 1 (NEFU); 43 – Tambana variegata, male genitalia, Vietnam, genit. prep. 378 Speidel (WS); 44 – Xanthomantis cornelia, male genitalia, South Korea, genit. prep. 94 - 1 (NIAST)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279002/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
Fig. 
<number box="[393,425,223,247]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="39.0">39</number>
</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName box="[447,691,224,248]" class="Insecta" family="Pantheidae" genus="Disepholcia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caerulea">
<emphasis box="[447,691,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Disepholcia caerulea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a similar ground plan of forewing coloration and pattern as 
<taxonomicName box="[151,275,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Pantheidae" genus="Trisuloides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,275,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Trisuloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; externally it differs from 
<taxonomicName box="[584,709,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Pantheidae" genus="Trisuloides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[584,709,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Trisuloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its larger size (wingspan 
<quantity box="[1052,1177,260,284]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.25" metricValueMax="7.5" metricValueMin="7.0" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" unit="mm" value="72.5" valueMax="75.0" valueMin="70.0">70–75 mm</quantity>
) and by having blackbrown with blue metallic hindwings, without yellow medial part and terminal band as in 
<taxonomicName box="[1138,1262,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Pantheidae" genus="Trisuloides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1138,1262,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Trisuloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName box="[249,384,332,356]" class="Insecta" family="Pantheidae" genus="Disepholcia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caerulea">
<emphasis box="[249,384,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">D. caerulea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[402,487,332,356]" captionStart="FIGURES 39 – 44" captionStartId="15.[151,263,1870,1893]" captionTargetBox="[151,1432,195,1813]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1436,195,1823]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 39 – 44. Discepholcia, Tambana, Xanthomanthis, adults and male genitalia. 39 – Discepholcia caerulea, male, Thailand (AP); 40 – Tambana variegata, male, Vietnam (GR); 41 – Xanthomantis cornelia, male, South Korea (NIAST); 42 – Discepholcia caerulea, male genitalia, China, genit. prep. HHL- 1767 - 1 (NEFU); 43 – Tambana variegata, male genitalia, Vietnam, genit. prep. 378 Speidel (WS); 44 – Xanthomantis cornelia, male genitalia, South Korea, genit. prep. 94 - 1 (NIAST)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279002/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
Fig. 
<number box="[457,487,332,356]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="42.0">42</number>
</figureCitation>
) is generally similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[765,889,332,356]" class="Insecta" family="Pantheidae" genus="Trisuloides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[765,889,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Trisuloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs by shape of editum, which is more strongly sclerotised than in 
<taxonomicName box="[469,593,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Pantheidae" genus="Trisuloides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[469,593,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Trisuloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, seen as a long, finger-like extension and by the shape of harpe which is strongly sclerotised, finger-like, positioned transversally and slightly arched basally. The aedeagus of 
<taxonomicName box="[1303,1436,404,428]" class="Insecta" family="Pantheidae" genus="Disepholcia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caerulea">
<emphasis box="[1303,1436,404,428]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">D. caerulea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is long, relatively thin, with sclerotised carina; vesica simple, tubular. The female genitalia of 
<taxonomicName box="[1199,1331,440,464]" class="Insecta" family="Pantheidae" genus="Disepholcia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caerulea">
<emphasis box="[1199,1331,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">D. caerulea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1347,1428,439,463]" captionStart="FIGURES 67 – 71" captionStartId="21.[151,263,1873,1896]" captionTargetBox="[266,1399,193,1795]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[151,1436,193,1821]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 67 – 71. Trisuloides and Disepholcia, female genitalia. 67 – T. sericea, North India, genit. Prep. Z 4219 GB; 68 – T. rotundipennis, South Korea, genit. prep. HHL- 480 a- 2; 69 – T. becheri, China, genit. prep. HHL- 1508 - 2; 70 – Discepholcia caerulea, China, genit. prep. HHL- 1766 - 2; 71 – Xanthomantis cornelia, Russia, Primorye terr., 1295 IBP." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279008/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
Fig. 
<number box="[1399,1428,439,463]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="70.0">70</number>
</figureCitation>
) differ by the presence of extremely large, strongly sclerotised antrum which is almost equal to corpus bursae in length, very short ductus bursae and presence of a postvaginal plate with two lateral extensions and small central bifurcate extension.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
